WEBVTT

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:23.000
TICK?"

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:27.000
WITH JOHN STOSSEL.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:29.000
THE TEEN YEARS ARE

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:30.000
AN AMAZING TIME.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:33.000
PUBERTY MAKES HORMONES RAGE,

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:34.000
SEXUAL PASSION EXPLODES, OFTEN

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:35.000
BEFORE THE ADOLESCENT HAS

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:36.000
THE WISDOM TO DEAL WITH IT.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:38.000
AND TEENS EXPERIENCE HUGE GROWTH

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:39.000
SPURTS.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:40.000
SO SUDDENLY, THEY'RE

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:42.000
IN A BRAND-NEW, MUCH BIGGER

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:43.000
BODY, WITH NEW DESIRES.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:46.000
WOW.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:48.000
**

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:49.000
IS IT SURPRISING THAT

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:50.000
THEY SOMETIMES DO STRANGE

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:51.000
THINGS?

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:52.000
WOO!

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:53.000
THIS IS A RAVE

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:55.000
IN CONNECTICUT, AN IMMENSE DANCE

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:56.000
PARTY WITH THROBBING ELECTRONIC

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:59.000
MUSIC.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:00.000
18-YEAR-OLD AURA DIMON OFTEN

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:01.000
DRIVES HOURS TO GET TO RAVES,

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:04.000
WHERE SHE'LL DANCE ALL NIGHT,

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:06.000
SOMETIMES UNTIL HER FEET BLEED.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:08.000
TO AN OLD GUY LIKE ME, THIS

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:10.000
SEEMS PRETTY STUPID, BUT IN ALL

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:12.000
THIS TEENAGE CRAZINESS THERE IS

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:14.000
AN ENERGY, A PASSION FOR LIFE

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:15.000
THAT OFTEN CREATES GOOD THINGS.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:17.000
**

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:18.000
AURA, FOR EXAMPLE, ISN'T JUST

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:20.000
HERE TO DANCE.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:21.000
SHE'S TAKING PICTURES

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:23.000
FOR INSPIRATION BECAUSE SHE HAS

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:24.000
HER OWN CLOTHING BUSINESS.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:27.000
AND IT'S A SUCCESSFUL ONE.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:28.000
THE KIDS, THEY WILL BUY

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:29.000
WHATEVER SHE PUTS OUT AT THIS

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:30.000
POINT.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:31.000
IT'S COOL.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:32.000
**

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:33.000
Reporter: A NEW YORK

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:35.000
NIGHTCLUB HOSTS A FASHION SHOW

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:36.000
OF HER DESIGNS.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:37.000
SHE'S SUCCESSFUL, SOME PEOPLE

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:39.000
SAY, BECAUSE HER TEENAGE PASSION

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:40.000
GIVES HER THE ENERGY TO WORK

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:41.000
HARDER THAN OLDER DESIGNERS.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:43.000
HOW MANY HOURS A DAY DO

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:44.000
YOU SPEND THINKING

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:46.000
ABOUT OR WORKING ON CLOTHING?

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:47.000
ALMOST EVERY SINGLE HOUR

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:48.000
OF MY LIFE.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:49.000
Reporter: SOME DAYS SHE'LL

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:51.000
DESIGN FOR TEN STRAIGHT HOURS.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:52.000
'CAUSE THIS IS WHAT MAKES ME

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:53.000
HAPPY.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:55.000
MY QUESTION IS, WHAT IS THIS?

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:56.000
Reporter: AND SOME SAY SHE'S

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:57.000
SUCCESSFUL BECAUSE AS A TEEN,

00:01:57.000 --> 00:01:59.000
HER YOUNG MIND IS MORE OPEN

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:01.000
TO NEW IDEAS, LIKE PANTS MADE

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:04.000
OUT OF SHOWER CURTAINS

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:05.000
OR CONSTRUCTION MESH.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:07.000
SHE INVENTS NEW THINGS THAT

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:08.000
YOUNG PEOPLE CAN'T GET

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:09.000
ENOUGH OF.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:11.000
THESE ARE REALLY COOL.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:12.000
THIS TYPE OF THING

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:13.000
EXCITES ME.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:14.000
Reporter: THIS DOESN'T EXCITE

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:16.000
YOU?

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:16.000
NOT REALLY, JOHN.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:18.000
I DON'T WANT A SEAM IN THE BACK.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:19.000
WELL, YOU SEE THE WAY IT'S

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:20.000
TAILING OUT BACK HERE?

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:21.000
I LIKE THAT, THOUGH.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:22.000
Reporter: BEAU BAKER, WHO

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:22.000
FINANCED HER, HAS TO DEAL

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:24.000
WITH HER DEMANDS THAT EVERYTHING

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:26.000
BE DONE HER WAY.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:27.000
AS WE GET OLDER, I THINK

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:29.000
WE LEARN TO BE AFRAID OF THINGS.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:30.000
AND SHE HASN'T GOT THAT.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:32.000
SO EVERYTHING SHE DOES, SHE DOES

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:33.000
WITH A HUGE AMOUNT OF PASSION.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:34.000
WE'VE GOT TO TRY TO DO IT.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:35.000
IT'S A BLESSING AND IT'S

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:37.000
A CURSE.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:38.000
I JUST HAVE TO HAVE THE SENSE

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:39.000
TO HOLD ON TIGHT ENOUGH AND MAKE

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:41.000
SURE THAT SHE DOESN'T JUMP OFF

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:43.000
A CLIFF.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:45.000
Reporter: WHAT WE ADULTS CALL

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:46.000
JUMPING OFF A CLIFF MAY BE JUST

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:47.000
A TEENAGER USING HER EXTRA

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:49.000
PASSION AND OPEN MIND TO CREATE

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:51.000
NEW THINGS.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:52.000
TEENAGE CHESS PRODIGIES

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:55.000
BOBBY FISCHER AND GARY KASPAROV

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:56.000
FOUND ATTACKS THEIR ELDERS NEVER

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:58.000
CONCEIVED OF.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:02:59.000
JARON LANIER WAS 15 WHEN

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:00.000
HE INVENTED THE COMPUTER

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:03.000
SIMULATION VIRTUAL REALITY.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:05.000
PICASSO WAS JUST 14 WHEN

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:07.000
HE PAINTED MASTERPIECES LIKE

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:08.000
THIS.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:12.000
TODAY, IN WHITTIER, CALIFORNIA,

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:13.000
13-YEAR-OLD ALEXANDRA NECHITA IS

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:14.000
SOMETIMES CALLED "THE PETITE

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:15.000
PICASSO."

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:17.000
SHE PAINTS PICTURES SOME CALL

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:18.000
MIRACULOUS.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:19.000
SHE'S SOLD SOME FOR MORE THAN

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:21.000
$100,000.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:22.000
I JUST HAVE TO PAINT.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:23.000
IT JUST COMES OUT.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:24.000
NOW, IT'S JUST WHOOSH, WHOOSH,

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:25.000
WHOOSH.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:27.000
THERE IS SO MUCH ENERGY WITHIN

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:28.000
ME THAT I JUST KEEP ON GOING

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:29.000
AND GOING AND GOING.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:31.000
Reporter: HER TEENAGE PASSION

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:32.000
IS PART OF IT.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:34.000
SHE PAINTS FOR HOURS EVERY DAY.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:36.000
BUT SHE ALSO HAS THAT CHILDISH

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:38.000
DETERMINATION TO DO JUST WHAT

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:39.000
SHE WANTS, NO MATTER WHAT

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:40.000
OTHERS SAY.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:42.000
ALEXANDRA'S CLASSMATES MOCKED

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:43.000
HER BECAUSE HER DRAWINGS WERE

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:45.000
STRANGE.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:49.000
SHE JUST KEPT PAINTING.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:50.000
THAT'S FANTASTIC.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:51.000
Reporter: NOW, HER WORK HANGS

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:53.000
IN GALLERIES AROUND THE WORLD.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:54.000
ANDRE AGASSI JUST BOUGHT ONE.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:55.000
LAST YEAR, 12 YEARS OLD,

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:56.000
NOW 13.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:58.000
SHE'S REMARKABLE.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:00.000
ADULTS PUT STOPS

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:01.000
TO THEIR IMAGINATION

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:04.000
BECAUSE THEY'RE AFRAID THAT

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:05.000
IT'LL DO THIS OR IT'LL DO THAT.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:06.000
BUT CHILDREN ARE SO INNOCENT.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:08.000
THEIR MIND'S ALWAYS EXPLODING

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:10.000
WITH NEW IDEAS, NEW IDEAS.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:11.000
THEY HAVE NO LIMITS IN LIFE.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:13.000
Reporter: ARE TEENAGERS

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:14.000
REALLY THAT DIFFERENT

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:16.000
FROM ADULTS?

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:17.000
WELL, YES, SAY RESEARCHERS HERE

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:18.000
AT HARVARD MEDICAL SCHOOL'S

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:19.000
BRAIN IMAGING CENTER.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:20.000
SIT RIGHT DOWN.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:21.000
LIE BACK.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:22.000
GET NICE AND COMFORTABLE.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:23.000
Reporter: HERE, THEY PUT

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:24.000
TEENAGERS, AND THEN PEOPLE

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:26.000
MY AGE, INTO THE MRI SO THEY CAN

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:28.000
WATCH HOW OUR BRAINS WORK.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:30.000
OKAY.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:31.000
YOU'RE ALL SET?

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:32.000
Reporter: ALL SET.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:33.000
ALL RIGHT.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:33.000
HERE WE GO.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:34.000
STAY NICE AND STILL.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:35.000
Reporter: THE DOCTOR

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:36.000
IN CHARGE,

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:37.000
DEBORAH YURGELUN-TODD, SAYS WHEN

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:38.000
I AND OTHER ADULTS ANSWER

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:39.000
QUESTIONS, WE USE THE RATIONAL,

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:41.000
THINKING PART OF OUR BRAIN.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:42.000
THE DORSAL-LATERAL PREFRONTAL

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:43.000
CORTEX.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:44.000
Reporter: AND THE TEENAGERS

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:45.000
USE A DIFFERENT PART?

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:46.000
RIGHT.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:47.000
RIGHT.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:50.000
KIDS USE THE REGION BEHIND HERE,

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:52.000
CALLED THE AMYGDALA.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:53.000
Reporter: THAT'S

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:55.000
THE INSTINCTUAL PART

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:56.000
OF THEIR BRAIN, AND THIS MAY

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:57.000
EXPLAIN THEIR CREATIVITY.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:04:58.000
SOME OF OUR BETTER CREATIVE

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:00.000
WORKS OCCUR DURING THIS TIME

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:01.000
OF LIFE BECAUSE THERE'S NOT THAT

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:01.000
SENSE OF "I SHOULDN'T DO THIS"

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:02.000
OR "I CAN'T DO THIS."

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:04.000
**

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:05.000
Reporter: LOOK HOW MUCH

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:06.000
ORIGINAL MUSIC IS CREATED

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:07.000
BY TEENS.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:08.000
MICHAEL JACKSON WON MALE

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:10.000
VOCALIST OF THE YEAR WHEN

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:11.000
HE WAS 13.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:14.000
**

